# Memory Management Standards

Read `docs/standards/engineering/memory-management.md` before modifying allocator or memory code.

## Allocator Types

- `hu_system_allocator()` -- long-lived objects (config, vtables, process-lifetime data)
- `hu_arena_t` -- per-turn ephemeral data (prompt assembly, JSON building, context). Bulk-freed via `hu_arena_destroy()`
- `hu_tracking_allocator_t` -- tests only. Assert `hu_tracking_allocator_leaks(ta) == 0`

## Ownership Rules

- Creator owns -- whoever allocates is responsible for freeing
- `_owned` flags on results -- `output_owned = true` means caller frees; `false` means borrowed/static
- Every vtable type has a `_destroy` or `_deinit` cleanup -- always call it
- Never return pointers to stack locals or temporaries

## Cleanup Pattern

Use goto-cleanup for functions with multiple allocations:

```c
hu_error_t err = HU_OK;
char *buf = alloc->alloc(alloc->ctx, 256);
if (!buf) { err = HU_ERR_OOM; goto cleanup; }
// ...work...
cleanup:
    if (buf) alloc->free(alloc->ctx, buf, 256);
    return err;
```

## Critical Rules

- Free in reverse allocation order
- Never individually free arena-allocated pointers -- let `hu_arena_destroy()` handle it
- Use `SQLITE_STATIC` (null), never `SQLITE_TRANSIENT`
- Zero ASan errors required -- leaks, overflows, use-after-free are build failures
